Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

# 1. remove items with Not given rating
df_q13_1 = df[df['rating']!="Not given"].copy()

# 1b. Convert ratings datatype from strings to numbers
#df_q13_1['rating'] = df_q13_1['rating'].astype('int')
df_q13_1['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df_q13_1['rating'], errors='coerce')

# 2. Find mean of ratings for each restaurant
# without reset_index() -- doesn;t create a proper table in that case
df_avg = df_q13_1.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['rating'].mean().reset_index()

# 3. Find restaurants with mean rating  > 4
df_avg_rating_gt_4 = df_avg[df_avg['rating'] > 4]

# 4. Create another df with total counts of ratings for each restuarant
df_counts = df_q13_1.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['rating'].count().reset_index()
# find list of restaurants with ratings count >  50
df_counts_gt_50 = df_counts[df_counts['rating']>50]

# 5. Find common restaurants in the 2 dataframes
common_df = set(df_counts_gt_50['restaurant_name']).intersection(df_avg_rating_gt_4['restaurant_name'])

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [66]:
# Function to calculate profit when order cost > 20 / > 5 and  <=5
def calc_profit(x):
  if x > 20:
    return x * 0.25
  elif x > 5:
    return x * 0.15
  else:
    return 0

#Apply calc_profit function to each order and create another column having the profits per order
df['profits']= df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calc_profit)
# Add up  the profits of all order
print('profit = ', df['profits'].sum(), 'USD')

profit =  6166.303 USD

Observations:¶

Net revenue or Profit = 6166.30 USD

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • More than twice the number of orders are on weekends compared to Weekday
  • Max value of orders is a little higher on weekdays
  • Orders with cost around 22.5 USD result in 75% of the best ratings (This trend implies Korean, Mediterranean, and Viet cuisines might result in lower ratings)
  • Southern cusine has a higher range of prices followed by indian/spanish/middle-eastern
  • Customer ratings are not dependent on food_preparation_time or delivery_time
  • Ratings are better when the "Price-Range" of dishes offered is more
  • Delivery time is 5 mins more for 50% of weekday orders.
  • 75% of deliveries happen in 28 mins.
  • Average orders per customer = 1.58
  • Of the people that have given a rating, most number of people have given 5.
  • Food prep time and delivery time has no impact on ratings
  • No major correlation between numericals (cost_of_order , total_time, and rating)

Recommendations:¶

  • For Existing Hi-Paying Customers: Give promotional offers to customers (to increase average orders per existing customer) for ordering from restaurants having their major share of the range of orders around 22.5 USD / more than 20USD (resulting in max profit) for restaurants where they frequently order from and for restaurants with highest ratings. Have a loyalty program for existing customers. Also give them incentives for providing ratings on new orders

  • For Existing Low-Paying Customers: Since 75% of orders are below 20USD, for the low paying customers, provide free delivery and other such offers on orders with a higher price-range ie, if they order > 20 USD to enable them to try out higher price ranges, for example, in the same restaurants where they order (eg: Southern cusine has a higher range of prices followed by indian/spanish/middle-eastern, enabling customers to try out costlier dishes there)

  • For New Customers: Promotions to new customers restaurants with a higher range of prices - eg: Southern followed by indian/spanish/middle-eastern, to onboard customers who are hesistant. Once they have made a purchase, promote next restaurants with maximum rating data and higher prices (eg: American, Japanese, Italian, Chinese cuisines). Once purchases are made, no discounts to be offered for these cuisines but offer them incentives for providing ratings on good restaurants

  • For Good Restaurants/Businesses: Promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants with cusine_type: American , Japanese, Italian, and Chinese (since these have max ratings and bring in maximum profit)

  • For New Restaurants/Businesses: If they are American, Japanese, Italian, Chinese cuisines, give them promo offers since they are likely to bring in more high-paying customers, bringing in more profit

  • For Well-performing Restaurants/Businesses: Promo offers to top 5 restaurants in terms of the number of orders received

  • Logistics : On weekends where there are more orders, Organise delivery order pickup such that orders are picked for delivery first from restaurants having fastest food_prep_time , and orders from restaurants having slowest food_prep_time are picked up last. Multiple orders to be picked up by the same delivery vehicle.

  • Logistics: If there are large number of drivers waiting for an order, dynamically / realtime provide offers on restaurants with the fastest food_prep_time, esp. on weekends where there more orders.

  • For Dissatisfied Customers who gave ratings 1,2,3: Provide freebies/discounts on restaurants with rating > 4 so as to onboard them as customers.
